ETHEKWINI municipality mayor Mxolisi Kaunda is fuming after protesters burned down seven vehicles belonging to the municipality in the early hours of this morning. The incident left Kaunda angry happened at Cato  Manor's municipality offices. A group of protesters who are allegedly members of Abahlali baseMjondolo broke into the building and forced three security to lay down before setting vehicles on fire. In a statement issued by the mayor's office Kaunda strongly condemned the incident. He said what makes more angry is that this incident comes just after several state vehicles were also set alight in a Sizakala Centre in Lamontville recently. “We are concerned about this criminal behaviour of some members of the public.  "It is worrying because this unlawful conduct is not relenting. This is tax payers’ money and resources that are supposed to assist us in speeding up service delivery. "We therefore appeal to the police to leave no stone unturned and arrest those responsible for this crime. We also urge members of the community not to be silent when incidents of this nature happen in their communities. "They need to isolate these individuals by working unwaveringly with the police,” said Kaunda. A source in the area, who asked not to be named, said Abahlali baseMjondolo were revenging their demolition of their shacks by the municipality's land invasion unit The mayor said he will not tolerate  lawlessness and it is municipality's responsibility to act wherever it rears its ugly head because this is a country governed by the rule of law. Cops spokeswoman Colonel Thembeka Mbele said a case of malicious damage to property was opened at Cato Manor police station for investigation. She said a group of people carrying petrol  containers entered the building and set cars alight. Attempts to get Abahlali leader Sbu Zikode failed.